<P>
Photo, More foreigners visited Korea for the 1988 Olympics than had done so in 
all of the 20th Century to that point. The resulting scrutiny, during the 
months that preceded the games, became a weapon in the hands first of student 
demonstrators and later of others who brought democracy to Korea. The story of 
their victory is captured in "From the Streets to the Olympics: Korea, 
Democracy and the 24th Olympiad, 1987-88" (Art Space Publications, P.O. Box 
74-1447, Los Angeles 90004; 300 pp.), a book of extraordinary photographs by 
Hyungwon Kang, who clearly took some of his photographs at great personal risk. 
With a brief opening text and well-placed captions in Korean as well as 
English, the book is a unique memorial to a historic transition. 
</P>
