<P>
TV Times; Page 13; Television Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
933 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
'THE POOL HALL' TAKES ITS CUE ON A&amp;E CABLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Mary Campbell, The Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
James Earl Jones, who plays a pool hall owner in "Third and Oak: The Pool 
Hall," has a pool table in his suburban home. He piles books on it. But, in 
case his 6-year-old son ever wants to learn to play, it's there. 
</P>
<P>
"Third and Oak: The Pool Hall," a three-character play by Marsha Norman, will 
be shown on the Arts &amp; Entertainment cable network Thursday (6 p.m. and 10 
p.m.) and again next Sunday. It's the first of four hourlong plays by Pulitzer 
Prize-winning playwrights to be shown on A&amp;E on the first Thursday of every 
month through February as "American Playwrights Theatre," a GM Mark of 
Excellence presentation. 
</P>
<P>
The play takes place in a run-down pool hall that Jones' character is preparing 
to sell. His best friend's son (Mario Van Peebles) stops by and what starts out 
as a casual chat turns to more intimate talk of secrets, promises, friendship 
and the high cost of loyalty. 
</P>
<P>
At first, Jones wasn't sure he wanted to play the character, saying he likes to 
portray people who are worthwhile. "That was the problem here. I had to accept 
he was a jerk. I'm playing not a villain but not a right guy. I had to readjust 
my thinking. 
</P>
<P>
"He is one of the blind ones. I defined Troy Maxson in 'Fences' (Jones played 
Maxson on Broadway) as a man who didn't distinguish his principles from his 
prejudices. This is such a man. He seemed gratuitously racialist if not racist 
when it came to references to people outside his race, particularly to the girl 
who visits the pool hall. She is blond. She qualifies, in his eyes, for 
derision. 
</P>
<P>
"I had a problem with that. I don't like to promote gratuitous racialism at 
all." 
</P>
<P>
"I had to understand that white people had never meant anything good to him. He 
can't understand how on a romantic level they can mean something good to a 
young man he thinks of essentially as his son. He can't see genuine affection 
and love between people who come from different worlds. 
</P>
<P>
"My character, who's in a closed society, behaves as if he's a Mafia don. He 
expects obedience and the mantle to be passed." 
</P>
<P>
In addition to Mario Van Peebles (of the TV series "Sonny Spoon"), the cast 
features Debra Cole. 
</P>
<P>
The author, Marsha Norman, won the Pulitzer Prize in 1983 for " 'night Mother." 
The other playwrights to be represented in the series are Eugene O'Neill, Paul 
Zindel and Tennessee Williams. 
</P>
<P>
Jones has been around a long time, but he said that doesn't mean good scripts 
are going to come "flowing your way in excess. There are more good actors than 
good works." 
</P>
<P>
But the actor stays busy. He was a poet in the film "Field of Dreams," played 
civil-rights leader Vernon Jordan in the first installment of "Saturday Night 
With Connie Chung" on CBS and recently narrated "Ivory Wars," about African 
elephants, on the Discovery cable channel. 
</P>
<P>
He has made several movies, not yet released, since "Field of Dreams." "I have 
a 6-year-old. I have to keep working. I don't make multimillions per movie. I 
don't think anybody should, frankly," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The veteran actor was complimentary about the young crowd of actors coming up. 
"The young man who played my son in 'Fences,' Courtney Vance, is in 'Hamburger 
Hill.' It's on cable and I've seen it five times to see his scenes. He's a 
phenomenal actor. He ranks with young actors like Eric Roberts, Terence Booth, 
Alec Baldwin, Kevin Costner. They're strong without being macho bulls. They're 
strong as people." 
</P>
<P>
Jones next is going to Louisiana to play a man who runs a store in the movie 
"Convicts." The wardrobe mistress told him to bring clothes that he wore in 
"Matewan," which was about coal miners in the 1920s. 
</P>
<P>
Some moviegoers recognized his voice as Darth Vader in "Star Wars," though the 
credits listed the actor inside the costume and helmet. Using his voice was an 
afterthought, after the movie was shot, Jones said. "I didn't feel it was 
proper for me to take credit. I had been a member of the board of directors of 
the Academy of Motion Pictures Arts and Sciences when Mercedes McCambridge's 
voice was in Linda Blair's body in 'The Exorcist.' 
</P>
<P>
"I didn't want to get involved with that sort of thing again. I denied it 
during the whole exposure of the first episode. I took credit in the third 
('Return of the Jedi') because I was going to be bumped off." 
</P>
<P>
When a criticism that black voices shouldn't be used for villains is quoted, 
Jones erupts. "That's a racialist point of view, as destructive, limiting and 
negative as racism is. I heard a lot of it. That's when black people who need a 
platform can't find anything better to talk about. That's embarrassing. There 
are a lot of really important issues and they had to light on that to talk 
about." 
</P>
<P>
Jones, whose training was on stage, mostly acts in movies and TV now. "The 
energy factor gets more and more difficult. I'm not happy unless I have a role 
that's totally engaging. I commit for more than six months and I get burned 
out. If I did a small part I'd be happier, but I wouldn't be able to make a 
living from it. 
</P>
<P>
"So I will do less stage work, only special things and probably short 
engagements. I think my days of commercial theater are probably coming to an 
end. I'll go to pasture in movies and TV." 
</P>
<P>
But he won't retire. "When we stop doing, we stop being. Most actors can keep 
functioning till they can't walk any more." 
</P>
<P>
He says with a laugh that he's considering modifying his rich, deep voice for 
TV commercials. "I just finished doing the voice of a car. They wanted a kind 
of Darth Vader voice. I did enjoy doing those commercials. I will have to look 
for another road to do commercials. Maybe some squeaky voice. I don't know." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, James Earl Jones plays a pool hall owner in "Third and Oak: The Pool 
Hall" Thursday at 6 p.m. and 10 p.m. on Arts &amp; Entertainment's "American 
Playwrights Theatre." 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102989-0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 127101 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 29, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 15; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1630 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENDPAPERS: WOMEN SLEUTHS AND THE RISE OF THE WHYDUNIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHARLES CHAMPLIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The tidings at this year's Bouchercon, a recently concluded annual encampment 
of mystery writers and mystery lovers, was not simply that the mystery field is 
burgeoning (nearly 1,500 titles in 1988, according to a tabulation by the Drood 
Review of Mystery in Boston). The news within the news, so to speak, was that 
women are not only writing mysteries, they are writing mysteries with female 
protagonists. 
</P>
<P>
In his history of crime fiction, "Mortal Consequences," Julian Symons 
identifies Ann Katharine Green as the first American woman to write a detective 
novel, "The Leavenworth Case," in 1878. Green's father was a criminal attorney 
and her research was near at hand. Among the English pioneers was F. Tennyson 
Jesse, a grandniece of Lord Alfred. She wrote a series of stories about an 
amateur detector named Solange Fontaine. 
</P>
<P>
In modern times, women have had an importance in the field quite 
disproportionate to their numbers. Any popularity poll of mystery writers in 
the 20th Century would surely put Agatha Christie at the top, with Dorothy L. 
Sayers, Margery Allingham, Josephine Tey and Ngaio Marsh high on the list. P. 
D. James, Ruth Rendell, Martha Grimes, Amanda Cross, Antonia Fraser, Dorothy 
Salisbury Davis (honored here at Bouchercon) and Mary Higgins Clark might lead 
a list of active writers. 
</P>
<P>
Yet in the reading if not in the writing, the mystery was taken to be a man's 
game. Although she later invented Jane Marple and the husband-and-wife team of 
Tommy and Tuppence Beresford, Agatha Christie established her fame and her 
readership with Hercule Poirot (whom she later found exasperatingly tiresome). 
Sayers' creature was the archly mannered Lord Peter Wimsey, and while his wife 
Harriet Vane received increasing attention and was by no means a stereotyped, 
reactive figure, the series was essentially all Wimsey. Allingham spent more 
than 30 years with the deceptively vacuous Albert Campion (now emerging on 
television). Ngaio Marsh's man was Roderick (Rory) Alleyn. P. D. James 
generally writes about Adam Dalgliesh, with just one outing thus far for a 
woman, Cordelia Gray, in "An Unsuitable Job for a Woman." 
</P>
<P>
Rendell's series characters are Inspector Wexford and his sidekick Mike Burden. 
Grimes has given us Richard Jury. And so it has gone. 
</P>
<P>
But the job is no longer thought unsuitable for women. In England, Amanda 
Fraser broke the pattern decisively with her Jemima Shore, a television 
personality who is an inadvertent sleuth but a clever one and who is as well 
the very model of the liberated woman, with a married lover to whom she is not 
subservient. 
</P>
<P>
Now the United States, where Dashiell Hammett and Raymond Chandler established 
a whole genre, has a commanding lead in generating a new genre, or a co-genre, 
in which remarkable, non-traditional women, often professional private eyes, 
work as crime-solvers in a style and milieu about as far as you can get from 
Nancy Drew. 
</P>
<P>
The nearest Drew equivalent, though only in the limited sense of being a 
well-mannered lady, would have to be Amanda Cross' Prof. Kate Fansler, an 
academic whose work-life presumably echoes that of Carolyn Heilbrun, the 
Columbia professor for whom Cross is the nom-de-crime. 
</P>
<P>
Nancy Pickard's Jennifer Cain is not a private eye but runs a civic foundation 
in a small Eastern city, a position from which she has no trouble stumbling 
onto greedy developers and other wellsprings of crime. 
</P>
<P>
But Fansler and Cain are anomalies. The new norm is the female private eye who, 
without sacrificing sensitivity, is in many details quite the same as her male 
forebears. The incomes tend to range from low to non-existent (one sleeps on 
the floor of her office). The investigating ladies endure many a beating, and 
they are as familiar with the dark, mean streets as ever Philip Marlowe or Sam 
Spade was. Above all, they are no less dedicated to discovering truth and 
seeing justice done, whether within the law or outside it. 
</P>
<P>
Sara Paretsky's V. I. Warshawkski was once a lawyer in the public defender's 
office. She is now a Chicago PI (private investigator, of course) whose cases 
run a gamut of hot social issues, from industrial pollution to incompetent 
medicine. 
</P>
<P>
At a panel discussion called "After Equality -- What?," Paretsky, who began 
writing after she earned a Ph.D. at the University of Chicago, said: "I'm sick 
of our being called women writers instead of just writers." 
</P>
<P>
She was asked if the new fictional women were too tough. " 'Are the women 
tough?' is a tough question," Paretsky said. "I've been re-reading all of 
Chandler. Marlowe is so alone. I. V. has connections. She can be weak and 
wounded and need help. In our society, tough means you're alone, and when you 
think about it, that's pretty sick." 
</P>
<P>
Sue Grafton of Santa Barbara writes about Kinsey Millhone, a private eye who 
first appeared in " 'A' Is for Alibi" in 1982 and has been working her way 
through the alphabet. Millhone could have had coffee with Ross Macdonald's Lew 
Archer, so similar is their milieu and the kind of personal, impassioned crime 
they encounter. 
</P>
<P>
Marcia Muller's Sharon McCone is a private investigator for a San Francisco law 
firm. Somewhat less well-defined than Millhone so far, she is a comparable 
mixture of sensibility and toughness and her detecting is not done from an 
armchair. 
</P>
<P>
Now as always, there seems no more fertile turf for the private eye than 
California. During Bouchercon, St. Martin's Press and the Private Eye Writers 
of America presented the fourth Best First Private Eye Novel award -- $10,000 
and publication by St. Martin's. It went -- for the fourth time -- to a 
Californian, Gar Anthony Haywood, whose "Fear of the Dark" will be published 
next year. The third winner, Karen Kijewski, is a former English teacher now 
tending bar in Citrus Heights to support her writing habit. Her heroine in the 
recently published "Walk" is Kat Colorado, a PI specializing in the corporate 
jungle, where she takes many a hard knock. 
</P>
<P>
A well-reviewed 1988 novel was "Donato &amp; Daughter" by Jack Early, about a 
weary NYPD detective who is outranked by and alienated from his daughter, an 
NYPD lieutenant. "Early," it was disclosed at Bouchercon, was in fact Sandra 
Scoppettone, who thought the pseudonym went better with a first-person male 
narrator. Her next book, Scoppettone told an audience, will be under her own 
byline and feature a lesbian detective. The dominance of male characters in 
crime fiction is eroding fast. 
</P>
<P>
The changing patterns in crime fiction are nicely symbolized by a new group 
called Sisters in Crime, which took form at a breakfast meeting at Bouchercon 
three years ago and now has 400 members, from writers to publishers. Organized 
by Sara Paretsky, the group agitates for equal review space for women writers 
(a sore point) and against gratuitous violence toward women in mysteries and 
all other fiction forms. 
</P>
<P>
The organization tabulated three years of crime-novel reviews in the New York 
Times and found only 14% of the books were by women. The Drood Review of 
Mystery made its own count of the 1988 mystery output. The journal found that 
of 1,487 titles published (or which came to their attention), 1,065 were 
written by men, 358 by women (a few others were by mixed teams or authors not 
identifiable by gender). The 3-1 ratio turned out to be the same ratio in which 
Drood itself reviewed books by men and women. 
</P>
<P>
(A rough count of the reviews in 24 monthly editions of "Bloody Sunday" in this 
newspaper showed the same ratio, 131 books by men, 45 by women, just about 3 to 
1.) 
</P>
<P>
Why women should have such an affinity to mysteries as both readers and writers 
is a lively question. Prof. B. J. Rahn of Hunter College, who teaches a course 
in crime fiction by women and who conducted a penetrating interview with Ruth 
Rendell at Bouchercon, noted some of the possible answers in a recent magazine 
piece. 
</P>
<P>
"Women," Rahn said in an interview, "are way out in front when it comes to the 
whydunit." They are themselves sensitive, she said, and they have insights into 
the deep emotions that can lead to acts of sudden rage or slow revenge. 
</P>
<P>
P. D. James, Rahn wrote, has observed that women "have a keen eye for the 
commonplace details used in constructing clues and spotting inconsistencies in 
suspects' stories." 
</P>
<P>
That women do the most reading is no surprise, says Rahn. "It's been that way 
for 200 years. They had the leisure to read. The novel was written for them, 
and of course the novel was not then thought to be real literature." 
</P>
<P>
It also may be that the leisure to write (or the traditional inability to find 
satisfying work in a male-dominated world) helped initially to explain the 
presence and the prestige of women in crime fiction. 
</P>
<P>
In the postwar years, Rahn has concluded, women have pioneered in the whydunit, 
taking the mystery from an intricate puzzle to a full-blown novel. "They have 
mastered the form with ease, wit and charm." 
</P>
<P>
Bouchercon, named after the late mystery writer-critic-anthologist Anthony 
Boucher, who preferred the name to his own William Anthony Parker White, this 
year had as honored guests Simon Brett, Ruth Rendell, Dorothy Salisbury Davis, 
the veteran editor Joan Kahn and H. R. F. Keating. The film of Keating's 
Inspector Ghote novel, "The Perfect Murder," was shown. It has no American 
distribution, although with all else it is a vivid look at present-day Bombay. 
This year's event, the 20th, drew about 250 writers, of whom half were women, 
and 750 fans, the clear majority of them women, as if to confirm tangibly what 
the surveys have been showing. 
</P>
<P>
At the panel on "After Equality -- What?" the participants agreed that crime 
fiction still was regarded as an inferior, stepchild literary form. Did they 
care? Panelists and audience in unison shouted a reverberating "No!" 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Ruth Rendell, one of the pattern-breakers. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
