<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE GODFATHER'S SON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Having opposed Brooklier in a loan-sharking case some years ago while I was a 
special attorney with the Organized Crime Strike Force, I have no quarrel with 
those who are impressed with the trial skills of the son of L.A.'s former don. 
It is the aura of glamour (or is it a halo?) that Murphy constructs around 
Brooklier that does a disservice to those who accept the burden of immigrant 
status without resorting to illegal activities to make their way. That Tony 
Brooklier's father may have been faced with the difficult and soul-searching 
choices of immigrants the world over does not excuse, or sanction, an end run 
around those barriers by the use of extortion and racketeering. I object to the 
rendering of criminal figures in sympathetic terms by the sleight of hand of 
humanizing the experience of someone like Tony Brooklier. I recall, with as 
equal and untainted an affection as Tony Brooklier has for his father, my 
grandfather pressing pants for 50 years in the poor but proud sections of 
Brooklyn for the munificent sum of $65 per week, 25 cents of which was usually 
shared with the grandchildren. A tattered picture of my grandfather with a sign 
reading "Please to tell your friends" in his tailor shop as he sought to 
scratch out a living on the Lower East Side trumpets more courage than an army 
of racketeers and hoodlums. 
</P>
<P>
GEORGE KARL ROSENSTOCK 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
