<P>
GREATER TUNA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kathie Jenkins 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sorry, Charlie, only good-tasting tuna gets to be served in these restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
Camelions, 246 26th St., Santa Monica. (213) 395-0746. Style: Romantic 
California-French. Setting: English rustic with cozy fireplace. Recommended 
dish: Rare charred tuna with black bean sauce, $21. 
</P>
<P>
Campanile, 624 S. La Brea Ave., Los Angeles. (213) 938-1447. Style: Rustic 
Italian serving trendy, simple and delicious food. Setting: High-tech romantic. 
Recommended dish: Appetizer of rare grilled tuna Nicoise, $7.75. 
</P>
<P>
Patina, 5955 Melrose Ave., Los Angeles. (213) 467-1108. Style: International 
with intellect. Setting: Fresh and bright. Recommended dish: Peppered tuna, 
$19.50. 
</P>
<P>
Pine Avenue Fish House, 100 W. Broadway, Long Beach. (213) 432-PINE. Style: The 
Pine Avenue Grill reincarnated into a seafaring creature. Setting: Cheery 
chintz. Recommended dish: Tuna steak sandwich, $8.95. 
</P>
<P>
Riva, at Loews Santa Monica Beach Hotel, 1700 Ocean Ave., Santa Monica. (213) 
458-6700. Style: Italian seafood and a view, sort of. Setting: Hotel standard. 
Recommended dish: Grilled tuna, $22.50. Kathie Jenkins 
</P>
