<HEADLINE>
<P>
IRVINE'S MEASURE N AND THE ISSUES OF HUMAN RIGHTS AND PRIVACY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Rev. Louis P. Sheldon's response (Oct. 15) to the editorial entitled "The 
Freedom to Decide" was, to say the least, quite interesting. 
</P>
<P>
The crux of his argument is that homosexuality is not prescribed in the genetic 
code. My question for the reverend is: Since when is bigotry contained in the 
genetic code? 
</P>
<P>
Sheldon states that the act of sodomy is the underlying connection of 
homosexuals. And I ask: Is prejudice not the common link of bigots? And most 
unfortunately, I know of no reparative therapy or medical treatment for those 
who desire change. 
</P>
<P>
KENT NEAL 
</P>
<P>
Laguna Beach 
</P>
