<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIMES BOARD OF ECONOMISTS / PAUL R. KRUGMAN: CAN WE AVERT THE NEXT FINANCIAL 
CRISIS? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAUL R. KRUGMAN, PAUL R. KRUGMAN is professor of economics at the 
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consider the following picture: It is a time of peace and prosperity, of 
capitalism triumphant. The Republican Party has overwhelmingly won the past 
three presidential elections, apparently establishing a permanent lock on the 
White House -- and why not, because Republican policies have brought steadily 
rising employment and consumption. Businessmen are the heroes of the age; 
organized labor is in retreat. 
</P>
<P>
There are, of course, a few blots on the picture. Battered by low export prices 
and the burden of their foreign debt, less developed countries do not share in 
the prosperity of the industrial world. Protectionist pressures are rising. 
There are strains on the international system because the traditional leader of 
the world economy is in relative decline, while the most economically dynamic 
major nation remains unwilling to take on its full responsibilities. 
Nonetheless, the fundamental picture is so strong that few would suppose that 
disturbances in the financial markets could produce more than a brief, mild 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
The year, of course, is 1929. Herbert Hoover is President. Britain is the 
declining leader of the international system, and the United States the dynamic 
nation unwilling to step into Britain's shoes. And the greatest economic 
catastrophe of modern history is about to happen. 
</P>
<P>
As the market hiccupped this year on Friday the 13th, the question that 
everyone asked two years ago came around once more: Can it happen again? 
</P>
<P>
A group of economists and policy-makers met recently in Cambridge, Mass., to 
discuss just that issue. Although the discussion was full of disagreements, and 
off the record anyway, I concluded several things from it. 
</P>
<P>
First, in a purely financial sense, crises on the scale of 1929 are if anything 
even more likely than they were 60 years ago. Black Monday in 1987 was actually 
worse than Black Thursday in 1929, and the global spread of the stock crash in 
1987 was faster and more complete than that of 1929. Computers and faster 
communications apparently don't make markets any more rational; they just allow 
panic to spread more efficiently. 
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the modest reforms undertaken since 1987 have done little if 
anything to reduce the vulnerability of the market to crashes. As it turned 
out, Friday the 13th didn't develop into a full replay of Black Monday -- but 
it certainly could have. 
</P>
<P>
On the more optimistic side, financial crises do not have to turn into real 
depressions. In October, 1987, a few sensible things were done, and the effect 
was to insulate the real economy almost completely from the effects of 
financial panic. 
</P>
<P>
Essentially, the Federal Reserve acted quickly to pour credit into the economy 
after the crash, abandoning for the time being both its monetary targets and 
any attempt to stabilize the dollar. Money growth accelerated to levels that 
horrified monetarists, and the dollar plunged 17% against the Japanese yen; but 
the crisis was contained. For most of the population, the stock market crash 
was purely a spectator event. 
</P>
<P>
What I learned from the historical discussion, however, was that the contrast 
between disaster in 1929 and successful containment of crisis in 1987 was not 
because of any fundamental change in the vulnerability of the economy. Had the 
Federal Reserve acted in 1929 as it did in 1987, there would almost surely have 
been no Great Depression. On the other hand, had the Federal Reserve acted in 
1987 the way it did in 1929, we would not now be shrugging the whole thing off 
as a temporary market aberration. The difference between then and now was 
primarily one of leadership, not institutions. 
</P>
<P>
The leaders deserve praise, of course, but it is worrisome when so much hangs 
on having a few men do exactly the right things. As one conference participant 
put it, we have relied on brilliant chairmen of the Federal Reserve to deal 
with financial crises twice in one decade; will our chairmen always be so 
brilliant? 
</P>
<P>
What is particularly worrisome is that many economic pundits advocate policies 
that would have ruled out the actions that insulated the real economy from 
financial panic in 1987. Suppose, in particular, that the kind of economists 
favored by the Wall Street Journal -- people such as Stanford's Ronald McKinnon 
or Columbia's Robert Mundell -- had been at the helm in the weeks after Black 
Monday. What would these people, whom we may refer to as "global monetarists," 
have done? The answer is, nothing -- or worse than nothing. 
</P>
<P>
As advocates of a real or simulated gold standard, they would have fiercely 
opposed the policy of rapid credit expansion that sterilized the real impact of 
the crash while driving down the dollar; this is especially true because the 
global monetarists insist on regarding the dollar as seriously undervalued. 
Since the crash would have placed downward pressure on the dollar even without 
a rapid credit expansion, and since this downward pressure would have been 
reinforced by speculation about possible future dollar depreciation, a global 
monetarist approach would actually have required a considerable credit 
contraction. 
</P>
<P>
The result would have been to turn the market slump into a major real slump as 
well. Probably our economy is not as depression-prone as the economy of 1929, 
but the result would still have been disastrous. 
</P>
<P>
The purpose of this scenario is not to emphasize how bad the economic analysis 
is at the Wall Street Journal or how bad the advice given by some economists is 
(although both points are true enough). Instead, the point is that we were all 
very lucky: The sensible and timely policies that actually averted disaster 
were carried out in the teeth of advice from seemingly reasonable and 
respectable voices. 
</P>
<P>
Someone once pointed out that the reason that the Romans, not the Greeks, ended 
up ruling the world was that while Hellenistic armies could perform miracles 
under brilliant leadership, Roman armies could manage adequately with mediocre 
generals -- which is more important in the long run. Unfortunately, we seem to 
have a Greek, not a Roman, world financial system. So the answer is yes -- it 
can happen again, though not under current management. 
</P>
<P>
Yet that was not the observation that most depressed me about the conference on 
crises. For the time being, at least, we seem to know what to do about stock 
market crashes and to have a leadership that is prepared to act on what we 
know. There is, however, another kind of international financial crisis: the 
kind of crisis that happens when a heavily indebted country's creditors decide 
that it is no longer a good risk. This is the kind of crisis that hit Latin 
America in 1982 and that may someday hit the United States. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, we do not seem to know how to manage debt crises. The same 
people who averted financial crises in 1982 and 1987 have attempted to deal 
with the Latin American problem for the past seven years. They have organized 
emergency loans, collective bargaining between debtors and creditors, 
international coordination on a grand scale. And the result? A decade of 
declining living standards, soaring unemployment and hyper-inflation. 
</P>
<P>
Latin America has done worse in the '80s than it did in the '30s. Predictions 
of a hard landing for the United States have so far not come true, but then 
people who worried about Third World debt were widely regarded as cranks right 
up to the moment of crisis. 
</P>
<P>
So there won't be a replay of 1929 in the near future; but if you want to see 
America turn into Argentina, it's a possibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102989-0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 127363 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 29, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Business; Part D; Page 2; Column 1; Financial Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1342 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WALL STREET / JOHN CRUDELE: EVEN THE PROS ARE FED UP WITH PROGRAM TRADING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN CRUDELE, JOHN CRUDELE is a financial columnist for the New York Post. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There is one consolation for the small investor whose confidence in the stock 
market might have been shaken by its volatility because of computerized program 
trading. Wall Street professionals -- the guys who make their living trading 
stocks -- aren't very happy with program trading either, and their confidence 
is also shot. 
</P>
<P>
"There is a high level of frustration right now regarding program trading," a 
trader for one of Wall Street's top brokerages said on the floor of the New 
York Stock Exchange. "This type of volatility is not good for anyone." His 
firm, incidentally, is one of the nation's biggest program traders. 
</P>
<P>
It isn't quite true that program trading helps no one. 
</P>
<P>
A volatile stock market, while it might do long-term damage to investor 
confidence, can be a bonanza for quick and agile money managers and traders who 
can instantly shift millions of dollars among stocks, bonds and equity futures 
and options. If you are playing the arbitrage game, then this volatility is 
perfect for you. 
</P>
<P>
Said one Wall Streeter: "They like the volatility. It gives them a chance to 
make money. It's the only way they can make money." 
</P>
<P>
And there is another short-term benefit of chaos: Brokerages are likely to reap 
extra commissions if small investors are scared into selling their stocks when 
the market hits one of its sinkholes. And they pocket another commission if the 
small investors decide to buy the stocks back, as they did on Oct. 16, once 
prices have fallen. But most Wall Street pros realize, after the tremors of the 
past week, that something has to change to keep the stock market from 
degenerating into the biggest gambling hall outside Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
"Even the pros have really had it. If they don't put an end to this, I don't 
know what will happen," another irate trader said. 
</P>
<P>
That opinion was widely shared last week. While many traders were willing to 
express their opinions, they all asked for anonymity. Their bosses, they 
assumed, still like program trading. 
</P>
<P>
This disdain for program trading among professionals is new. Most Wall 
Streeters have been tolerating program trading in much the same way that New 
Yorkers put up with slow traffic. If you can't do anything about it, why 
complain? 
</P>
<P>
Professional traders still may not be able to do anything about program 
trading, (especially now that the New York Stock Exchange is adding a program 
trading instrument of its own), but after this week, complaining about it makes 
them feel better. 
</P>
<P>
Kemper Financial Services, a Chicago-based company that manages about $57 
billion in assets, took its protest one step farther. It stopped doing business 
with four brokerages that use program trading for their own accounts. Late last 
week, Hartford, Conn.-based Phoenix Mutual Life, which manages more than $8.6 
billion in assets, said it refused to do business with firms using program 
trading. And Paine Webber said it will not execute program trading orders for 
customers; the Wall Street brokerage has not used program trading for its own 
account since May 1988. If you had to pinpoint when the pros' tolerance for 
program trading turned to hate, it was probably between 10:30 and 11 last 
Tuesday morning, when the Dow Jones industrial average started rallying from an 
unexpected 85-point deficit. The index ended that day at a loss of just under 4 
points, in what was one of the most volatile and perplexing sessions anyone 
could remember. 
</P>
<P>
"This industry is in a sad state of affairs," said yet another trader, who 
added that he, personally, isn't buying or selling many shares these days. 
"We're out of the market," he said. Why? He answered that it's too dangerous 
even for him. 
</P>
<P>
Here's what happened last Tuesday that got traders so upset: 
</P>
<P>
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. and Salomon Bros., two of Wall Street's biggest 
investment houses, that morning began selling bushels-full of stocks in 
asset-allocation programs, according to sources. An asset-allocation program 
uses computers to decide how much should be invested in stocks, bonds and other 
financial instruments. By allocating assets, Goldman Sachs and Salomon, for 
whatever reason, were simply deciding that it was time to sell stocks and buy 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
That burst of selling, along with the price of UAL stock going into another 
free fall, put the entire stock market on its ear and had even the coolest pros 
thinking that another crash was coming. 
</P>
<P>
Then, suddenly -- and mysteriously -- the selling stopped. 
</P>
<P>
Goldman, Sachs; Salomon and other brokerages turned on a dime and started 
buying huge volumes of stock through trading programs. The word on Wall Street 
was that regulators had warned the brokerage firms that they must "cease and 
desist" using computerized programs to unload stocks. But whether there was 
such a warning or this was simply Wall Street gossip, an attempt to explain the 
unexplainable, could not be determined. 
</P>
<P>
The change in direction Tuesday morning was so abrupt that even fleet-footed 
professional traders got caught by surprise. And with that, the pros all of a 
sudden could understand what small investors have been going through these past 
few years. 
</P>
<P>
The pros, almost in unison, started murmuring under their breath that they 
despised program trading as much as the next guy. 
</P>
<P>
"I hate the market," said a trader. "We are doing virtually nothing. The market 
is a big casino. If that's what they want to convey to the public, they should 
continue program trading." 
</P>
<P>
This sense of ire over program trading comes at an odd time. A strong case 
could be made that there is nothing keeping the stock market at current levels 
except programmed buying that kicks in whenever stock prices fall. 
</P>
<P>
The market will decline in time, anyway, but without an assist from the 
computers, stock prices would be falling right now, in reaction to the nation's 
weakening economy. 
</P>
<P>
By now even the most stubborn optimist realizes that companies aren't doing as 
well as they have been in recent years. But just how much has their profit 
performance deteriorated? 
</P>
<P>
Boston Co. has been keeping track of third-quarter profit reports during the 
past few weeks, and it thinks that if the current earnings trend continues, 
profits will be up a modest 6% this year. 
</P>
<P>
By comparison, profits risen around 20% a year for the past few years. 
</P>
<P>
That 6% growth this year, however, is mostly thanks to strong profits in the 
first quarter. Profits have been sliding all year, and third-quarter profits 
will probably be down 5% to 8% from last year's third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Earnings-per-share performance looks even worse, although in calculating 
earnings on a per-share basis, the figures are often skewed by extraordinary 
occurences such as one-time charges against earnings. 
</P>
<P>
Boston Co., meanwhile, thinks the worst is yet to come. Allen Sinai, its chief 
economist, says that "with the economy slowing down and labor costs still high, 
the squeeze on profits will continue. The outlook for corporate earnings in 
1990 would be flat to somewhat higher, at best." 
</P>
<P>
"That's a symptom and a possible cause of some sort of recession," he adds. 
</P>
<P>
Lower corporate profits, of course, should mean a weaker stock market. And the 
worse the profit picture gets, the harder the market is going to fall. 
</P>
<P>
Last week was the first time in a long while that the market started reacting 
to weak earnings. While the bond market rallied on the prospect of lower 
interest rates early last week, stock traders realized that borrowing costs 
would only fall because the economy is in bad shape. 
</P>
<P>
The stock market could soon be bothered by something else. According to the 
investment firm Lynch, Jones &amp; Ryan, the profits being reported by 
corporations are lower than Wall Street had expected. 
</P>
<P>
Often, the stock market will ignore poor earnings if it was expecting them, but 
it doesn't like to be surprised with bad news. 
</P>
<P>
Did you know that the estate of Elvis Presley earns $41,095.80 on an average 
day? President Bush earns $547.95. Those facts are from a strange but 
interesting new paperback full of tidbits, "On An Average Day" (Fawcett 
Columbine). . . 
</P>
</TEXT>
