<HEADLINE>
<P>
SIBERIAN ISLAND, WITH FEW AMENITIES, SEEKS INVESTORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
YUZHNO-SAKHALINSK, Soviet Union 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Soviet Union is trying eagerly to lure investors to Sakhalin, but foreign 
businessmen think Moscow is naive in thinking that foreigners will flock to the 
remote island off Siberia under present conditions. 
</P>
<P>
Sakhalin, in the Soviet Far East, opened to foreigners only last year, has 
recently played host to foreign businessmen, mostly from South Korea and Japan. 
</P>
<P>
But a gulf seems to separate the two sides on what comes first -- 
infrastructure or foreign investment. 
</P>
<P>
"This question of infrastructure may be solved only by foreign capital from 
joint ventures," said Ivan Kuropatko, a Sakhalin official. "The Japanese are 
hesitating just because they don't want to lose their money. There are no real 
obstacles (to investment)." 
</P>
<P>
"We think it's possible to establish joint ventures from zero by reorganizing 
certain existing enterprises and using foreign capital to modernize them," said 
economist Piotr Baklanov of the U.S.S.R. Academy of Sciences in Khabarovsk. 
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade official Valerian Timofeev said he believed that the rich 
resources of timber and fish on the island -- which lies some 25 miles to the 
north of Japan's northern island of Hokkaido and covers almost 30,000 square 
miles -- would provide the main lure to foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
An internal Japanese Foreign Ministry memorandum obtained by Reuters was 
doubtful that Japanese businessmen should leap into ventures in Sakhalin. 
</P>
<P>
"The Sakhalin authorities eagerly press for foreign joint ventures, but 
transport, accommodation and other infrastructure need to be taken care of by 
them beforehand," it said. 
</P>
<P>
The Japanese, wooed assiduously for their technology and money, worry that 
there is no clear-cut law or government policy on joint ventures, the memo 
noted. 
</P>
<P>
A Japanese official who visited the Soviet Far East recently said he was asked 
repeatedly by his Soviet counterparts why the Japanese are not flocking to 
invest there. 
</P>
<P>
He cited problems of communications -- three hours or more to place an overseas 
call. "That's even without a typhoon as an excuse," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"And after midnight, the water stops in these places," the official said. "On 
top of that, there's a labor shortage. How can you expect Japanese to put money 
into such a place?" 
</P>
<P>
It will take at least 20 years before the infrastructure could be in place -- 
unlike the three years predicted by the Soviets, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
H.K. Kang, a Tokyo-based South Korean businessman who was in Sakhalin to 
explore business opportunities, said he left without making a deal. 
</P>
<P>
"Although they talk about perestroika, their allocations of electricity, 
gasoline and other key things are totally inadequate," he said. 
</P>
<P>
He bemoaned a lack of precise data on local conditions. 
</P>
<P>
"I talked to many groups about population, etc., but everybody gave me 
different figures, especially on industry. This wouldn't work with the 
Japanese, who want precise data." 
</P>
<P>
So far, six joint ventures have been made, including a Japanese restaurant in 
the southwestern Sakhalin port of Kholmsk. The largest is a $26-million 
fish-processing plant venture, also with Japanese partners. 
</P>
<P>
One grave problem on Sakhalin is the complete lack of decent hotels to attract 
foreign businessmen or tourists. 
</P>
<P>
The shabby Tourist Hotel where a group of Western reporters stayed lacked hot 
water and had leaky toilets, with the water level rising to ankle-level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
